Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula has given Johannesburg's Lanseria International Airport his stamp of approval. The airport will now begin operating under level three of the lockdown. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Transport Minister Fikile Mbalula has given Johannesburg's Lanseria International Airport his stamp of approval. The airport will now begin operating under level three of the lockdown. Business travellers can once again take to the skies under level three of the lockdown. Lanseria International Airport is one of only four in the country that is opening. WATCH: Mbalula outlines public transport measures under level 3 Mbalula inspected the facility and explained how passengers will be received inside airports. “Only passengers will be allowed inside the terminal buildings therefore no accompanying members of the public will be allowed inside the terminal buildings. Temperature screening will be mandatory, you must be screened you must be checked and we have shown cased. Should you be a suspect and have the symptoms of coronavirus you are going to go through the procedures,” said Mbalula. Airports will have standby emergency aircraft and will have an Intensive Care Unit, in case someone needs it. READ: Limited domestic flights available under level 3 Planes are allowed to be filled to 100-percent capacity because they're using High-Efficiency Particulate Air filters. The airport has also implemented contactless security. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.